3.2 Process Safety Information - 68.65



The Warren Fractionation Plant keeps a variety of technical documents that are used to help maintain safe operation of the process.  These documents address chemical processes and associated hazards, limits for key process parameters, specific inventories, and equipment design basis/configuration information.  The Operations Manager has assigned responsibility for maintaining up-to-date process safety information.  Chemical-specific information, including toxicity information, permissible exposure limits, physical data, reactivity data, corrosivity data, and thermal/chemical stability data, is provided on the SDS (Safety Data Sheet).  SDS's are made available to all employees and contract personnel.  When applicable, this information is supplemented by documents that specifically address additional concerns.  The Warren Fractionation Plant also maintains information pertaining to the technology of the process.  The following process and equipment related information is available in the HAZOP (Hazard and Operability Study) of the Warren Fractionation Plant:



     1) A block flow diagram or simplified process flow diagram;

     2) Process chemistry;

     3) Maximum intended inventory;

     4) Safe upper and lower limits for such items as temperatures, pressures, flows, and compositions;

     5) An evaluation of the consequences of deviations;

     6) Materials of construction;

     7) Piping and instrument diagrams (P&ID's) and Process Flow Drawings (PFD's);

     8) Electrical classification;

     9) Relief system design and design basis;

     10) Ventilation system design;

     11) Design codes and standards employed;

     12) Material and energy balances for processes built after June 21, 1999;

     13) Safety systems (e.g. interlocks, detection or suppression systems, etc.);

     14) Documentation that equipment complies with recognized and generally accepted good engineering practices;

     15

) Equipment design, maintenance, inspection, testing, and safe operation;







3.3 Process Hazard Analysis - 68.67



PAPCO has completed a Process Hazard Analysis (hazard evaluation) on processes covered by this part.  PAPCO has determined and documented the priority order for conducting a Process Hazard Analysis based on a rationale which includes considerations such as;  extent of the process hazards, number of potentially affected employees, age of the process, and operating history of the process.  The PHA responds to 29 CFR 1910.119(e).  PAPCO utilized the following methodology appropriate to determine and evaluate the hazards of the process being analyzed.



Hazard and Operability Study (HAZOP) which addresses:



     1) The hazards of the process;

     2) The identification of any previous incident which had a likely potential for catastrophic consequences;

     3) Engineering and administrative controls applicable to the hazards and their interrelationships such as appropriate application of detection methodologies to provide early warning of releases; 

     4) Consequences of failure of engineering and administrative controls;

     5) Stationary source siting;

     6) Human factors;

     7) A qualitative evaluation of a range of the possible safety and health effects of failure of controls;



The Process Hazard Analysis was performed by a team with expertise in engineering and process operations.  Don Love, Ph.D, P.E. facilitated the initial/original effort.  Dr. Love has over 40 years of experience and knowledge specific to the process being evaluated.  PAPCO has established a system to promptly address the team's findings and recommendations.  PAPCO also assures that recommendations are resolved in a timely manner and resolutions are documented.  PAPCO developed a written schedule of when these actions are to be completed.  PAPCO has communicated the actions to operating, maintenance, and other employees whose work assignments are in the proce

ss and who may be affected by the recommendations or actions.  The Process Hazard Analysis will be updated and re-validated every 5 years, in accordance with CFR 1910.119(e), to assure consistency with the current process.  All MOC (Management of Change) items will be reviewed at the time of re-evaluation to ensure all process changes are evaluated for hazards and hazard controls.  The updates or re-validation for each process and the documented resolution of recommendations will be kept for the life of the process.







3.4 Operating Procedures - 68.69



PAPCO has developed and implemented written operating procedures that provide clear instructions for safely conducting activities involved in each covered process consistent with the process safety information.  The following elements are being addressed in the operating procedures:



     1) Steps for each operating phase;

     2) Initial startup;

     3) Normal operations;

     4) Temporary operations;

     5) Emergency shutdown including the conditions under which emergency shutdown is required and the assignment of shutdown responsibility to qualified operators to ensure that emergency shutdown is executed in a safe and timely manner.

     6) Emergency operations;

     7) Normal shutdown;

     8) Startup following a turnaround or after an emergency shutdown;

     9) Operating limits:

          i. Consequences of deviation;

          ii. Steps required to correct or avoid deviation;

     10) Safety and health considerations:

          i. Properties of and hazards presented by the chemicals used in the process;

          ii. Precautions necessary to prevent exposure, including engineering controls, administrative controls, and personal protective equipment;

          iii. Control measures to be taken if physical contact or airborne exposure occurs;

          iv. Quality control for raw materials and control of hazardous chemical inventory levels;

          v. Any special or unique hazards;

raining occurs regularly and verification is ascertained through observation, demonstration, and oral testing.







3.6 Mechanical Integrity - 68.73



The following process equipment is included in the PAPCO Mechanical Integrity program.



     1) Pressure vessels and storage tanks;

     2) Piping systems (including piping components such as valves);

     3) Relief and vent systems/devices;

     4) Emergency shutdown systems;

     5) Controls (including monitoring devices/sensors, alarms, and interlocks);

     6) Pumps;



PAPCO has established and implemented written procedures to maintain the on-going integrity of process equipment.  PAPCO trains each employee involved in maintaining the on-going integrity of process equipment.  The training provides an overview of each process, its hazards, and procedures applicable to the employee's job tasks.  Inspections and tests are performed on the regulated process equipment.  Inspection and testing procedures follow recognized and generally accepted good engineering practices.  The frequency of inspections and tests of process equipment is consistent with applicable manufacturers' recommendations and good engineering practices and more frequently, if determined to be necessary by prior operating experience.  In addition to the required inspection recommendations, PAPCO employees perform daily walk through's at the facility in order to identify potential hazards or concerns.  PAPCO documents each inspection and test performed on process equipment.  The documentation identifies the date of inspection or test, name of person who performed the inspection or test, and serial number or other identifier of the equipment on which the inspection or test was performed.  In addition, a description of the inspection or test performed and results of the inspection or test will be documented.  PAPCO corrects deficiencies in equipment that are outside acceptable limits (defined by the process safety information in 68.65) bef

ore further use or in a safe and timely manner when necessary means are taken to assure safe operation.



In the construction of new plants and equipment, PAPCO assures that fabricated equipment is suitable for the process application for which they will be used.  Appropriate checks and inspections are performed to assure that equipment is installed properly and consistent with design specifications and the manufacturer's instructions.  In addition, PAPCO will ensure that maintenance materials, spare parts, and equipment are suitable for the process application for which they will be used.







3.7 Management of Change - 68.75



PAPCO establishes and implements written procedures to manage changes (except for 'replacements-in-kind') to process chemicals, technology, equipment, and procedures along with changes to stationary sources that affect a covered process.  The procedures assure that the following considerations are addressed prior to any change:



     1) The technical basis for the proposed change;

     2) Impact of change on safety and health;

     3) Modifications to operating procedures;

     4) Necessary time period for the change;

     5) Authorization requirements for the proposed change;



Employees and contract employees involved in operating a process or maintenance whose job tasks will be affected by a change in the process, shall be informed of and trained in the change prior to start-up of the process or affected part of the process.  If a change results in a change in the process safety information required by 40 CFR 68.65 (process safety information), such information will be updated accordingly.  If a change results in a change in the operating procedures or practices required by 40 CFR 68.69 (operating procedures), such procedures or practices will be updated accordingly.







3.8 Pre Start-Up Review - 68.77



PAPCO performs pre-startup safety reviews for new stationary sources and modified stationary sources when the modif

ication is significant enough to require a change in process safety information.  The pre-startup safety review confirms that prior to the introduction of regulated substances to a process:



     1) Construction and equipment is in accordance with design specifications;

     2) Safety, operating, maintenance, and emergency procedures are in place and are adequate;

     3) For new stationary sources, a Process Hazard Analysis has been performed and recommendations have been resolved or implemented before startup.  For modified stationary sources, the requirements contained in 'Management of Change - 68.75' have been met;

     4) Training of each employee involved in operating a process has been completed;







3.9 Compliance Audits - 68.79



PAPCO will certify that they have evaluated compliance with the provisions of this subpart at least every three years.  PAPCO will also verify that procedures and practices developed under this subpart are adequate and are being followed.  The compliance audit will be conducted by at least one person knowledgeable in the process.  A report of the findings of the audit will be developed.  The owner or operator will determine and document an appropriate response to each of the findings of the compliance audit and deficiencies that have been corrected.  PAPCO will retain the two (2) most recent compliance audit reports.







3.10 Incident Investigation - 68.81



PAPCO health and safety personnel investigate each incident which resulted in, or could have reasonably resulted in, a catastrophic release of a regulated substance.  Incident investigations are initiated as promptly as possible, but not later than 48 hours following the incident.  In the event of such an incident, an investigation team is established.  The team consists of at least one person knowledgeable in the process involved, including a contract employee if the incident involved work of the contractor, and other persons with appropriate knowledge and

experience to thoroughly investigate and analyze the incident.  A report is prepared at the conclusion of the investigation and includes, at a minimum, the following:



     1) Date of incident;

     2) Date investigation began;

     3) A description of the incident;

     4) The factors that contributed to the incident;

     5) Any recommendations resulting from the investigation;



PAPCO has established a system to promptly address and resolve the incident report findings and recommendations.  Resolutions and corrective actions are documented.  In addition, the report is reviewed with all affected personnel whose job tasks are relevant to the incident findings.  The review also includes contract employees where applicable.  These incident investigation reports are retained for five years.







3.11 Employee Participation - 68.83



Employee participation is a key element of this program.  PAPCO has developed a written plan of action regarding the implementation of the employee participation.  PAPCO consults with employees and their representatives on the conduct and development of process hazards analysis and on the development of the other elements of process safety management in this rule.  PAPCO provides to employees and their representatives access to process hazard analysis and all other information required to be developed under this rule.







3.12 Hot Work Permit - 68.85



PAPCO issues a hot work permit for hot work operations conducted on or near a covered process.  The permit documents fire prevention and protection requirements in 29 CFR 1910.352(a) prior to beginning the hot work operations.  It indicates the date(s) authorized for hot work and identifies the object on which hot work is to be performed.  The permit is kept on file until completion of the hot work operation.







3.13 Contractors - 68.87



This section applies to contractors performing maintenance or repair, turnaround, major renovation, or specialty work on or adjace

nt to a covered process.  It does not apply to contractors providing incidental services which do not influence process safety such as janitorial work, food and drink services, laundry, delivery, or other supply services.



PAPCO develops and implements safe work practices consistent with 68.69(d).  PAPCO controls the entrance, presence, and exit of the contract owner or operator and contract employees in covered process areas.  Contractors are required to sign in and out when entering process areas.  Job Safety Analysis (JSA's) are generated to create awareness of hazards associated with specific tasks.  PAPCO personnel conduct regular informal 'tailgate meetings' in order to cover hazards associated with individual tasks.  In addition, PAPCO has held and will continue to hold formal meetings with contractors to cover safety expectations and obligations of the contract holder.  These activities and requirements allow PAPCO to inform the contract owner or operator of the known potential fire, explosion, or toxic release hazards related to the contractor's work and the process.  In addition, PAPCO explains the applicable provisions of 'Subpart E - Emergency Response' of this part.



PAPCO is developing methods that will improve its ability to evaluate contractor safety programs and performance.  PAPCO will ensure the contract owner or operator is fulfilling their obligations.  These obligations include:



     1) Assurance that each contract employee is trained in the work practices necessary to safely perform his or her job; 

     2) The contract owner or operator shall assure that each contract employee is instructed in the known potential fire, explosion, or toxic release hazards related to his or her job and the process and the applicable provisions of the emergency action plan;

     3) The contract owner or operator shall document that each contract employee has received and understood the training required by this section.  The contract owner or operator s

hall prepare a record which contains the identity of the contract employee, the date of training, and the means used to verify that the employee understood the training;

     4) The contract owner or operator shall assure that each contract employee follows the safety rules of the stationary source including the safe work practices required by 68.69(d);

     5) The contract owner or operator shall advise the owner or operator of any unique hazards presented by the contract owner or operator's work or of any hazards found by the contract owner or operator's work;
